Span.Text: Applications on mobile devices make collecting and organising evidence faster.  Features such as tagging evidence by tapping an evidence tag to create and store an evidence record make the process more efficient.  Evidence can then be managed along with images, videos and sound recordings to provide a more complete view of cases.

The use of mobile devices at the scene, enables the officer to capture evidence directly rather than writing notes and re-typing them later.  Photographic, audio and video evidence can be captured at the scene using the same digital device.
All notes are captured and stored in the cloud so they're immediately available for others to view.  Notes are captured at the scene, increasing the quality and saving time.

All information about a particular incident can be consolidated onto a single screen to make it easier for Officers to work with.  This includes all forms of evidence such as notes, audio, images and video.
A custody reference is entered to which the evidence will be linked.
A list of evidence items associated with this custody reference is shown.
Before an evidence bag can be tagged, information relating to the item of evidence is added.
The device is tapped onto a NFC tag on the evidence bag which writes the evidence information to the tag and creates a record in the evidence store.
